tool.name: CrossSections
tool.displayname: 2. Create Cross Sections and Routed Centerline

param.name: InputCenterline
param.datatype: Feature Layer or Feature Class or Shapefile
param.dialogReference:
First, we input the Centerline Feature Class created in Step 1. This feature should contain a single polyline feature that the user drew using Editor. The Centerline polyline must have a name saved in the ROUTEID column.

This step utilizes "routes" to give a linear measure to the centerline (1m steps).
param.pythonReference: Creates a variable that references the name of the Centerline Feature Class.

param.name: RouteID
param.dialogReference:
Next, we use the dropdown to select the ROUTEID. This is a maintenance/validation step to reduce potential user errors.

IMPORTANT!!! Do not draw more than one centerline feature!

Each evaluted centerline must be it's own feature class. So if you want to redo your centerline, rerun Step 1.

Failure to do so will likely result in a mismatch between the lenght of your centerline and the number of cross sections and stations created in this step.
param.pythonReference: Creates a variable that references the ROUTEID name.

param.name: OffsetLeft
param.dialogReference:
Now we input our Centerline Buffer Distance (m). This distance should ensure that each cross section extends to the valley toe slope.

These is not computational cost to extending your cross sections well beyond the toeslope. However, it dramatically increase the range of your relative elevations and make your inital stretched color ramp less informative.
param.pythonReference: Creates a variable that references the buffer distance (m).

param.name: DrawDirection
param.displayname: Select Direction to Start Stationing From
param.dialogReference:
Finally, we select the direction we would like to build our Centerline Stations from (i.e. moving upstream, or moving downstream) based on the drawn centerline and direction of flow.

Do you like your longitudunal profiles to rise or fall when moving from left to right?
param.pythonReference: Creates a variable that sets the route direction.

tool.summary:
This second tool utilizes the Centerline Feature Class to create a Routed Centerline and Cross Section polylines.

  1. First, we input the Centerline Feature Class created in Step 1. This feature should contain a single polyline with that the user drew using Editor. The Centerline polylinemust have a name saved in the ROUTEID column.

  2. Next, we use the dropdown to select the ROUTEID. This is a maintenance/validation step to reduce potential user errors.

  3. Then, we input our Centerline Buffer Distance (m). This distance sure ensure that each cross section extends to the valley toe slope.

  4. Finally, we select the direction we would like to build our Centerline Stations in (i.e. looking upstream, or looking downstream) based on the drawn centerline and direction of flow.

Define your Cross Section Polyline Feature Class widths.
